      "originalText": "You-Tube Top K\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n  1. Ingest views from KAFKA Stream and display TopK videos of all time.\n  2. Display TopK videos of tumbling window of 1 hour, 1 day or 1 month.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements\n   1. The system should prioritize availability over strong consistency (99.99%)\n   2. The TopK latency should be within 100ms - 200ms.\n   3. The system should be fault-tolerant and not prone to any data loss\n   4. With 70B views per day, we are expecting a TPS of 800K views/sec.\n   5. The view data should be ingested within a minute to update the TopK.\n\n\nAPI Routes\n\n1. GET videos/TopK?k=<count>&windowPeriod=<hour/month/day>&startTimestamp=<>\n\nList<>\n{\n     videoId\n     Rank:\n     viewsCount:\n     uploadedTimestamp\n     Creator:\n}\n\n2. POST views/ --> confirmationID (for ingestion) and status code\n\n{\n     viewId     \n     videoId\n     timestamp \n}\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n1. Ingest views from KAFKA Stream \n      a. The VIEW KAFKA stream will pass on the views to the Ingestion Service.\n      b. The ingestion service can sanitize the views message such as all the fields of the \n           Data structure are present - videoId, timestamp, viewId.\n      c. The Ingestion Service can directly write to the Database but given the scale of \n          800K views/sec, the Database would be completely bottleneck. \n      d. To avoid bottleneck, we can add a Kinesis Stream in between. The Kinesis has a\n           throughput of 1GB/sec. Given we have 800K views/sec and each VIEW Data structure\n           is of 1 KB, the total load would be around 800 MB/sec which is manageable for Kinesis Stream.\n      e. The Event Aggregator would be the major help in reducing the bottleneck as it will aggregate the\n           view count based on videoID for a tumbling window period of 1 hour, 1 day and 1 month.\n      f. Once the window is over, KDA has a functionality to directly write to the Database.\n      g. So, instead of making 800K calls per sec to the database, we are now making a max of 1 call to the\n          Database per hour.\n      h. Both Ingestion Service and the Event Stream can be sharded based on videoId so that the Kinesis can \n          accumulate the views of a single video in the same shard. If that's possible and we end of creating\n          another shard of the same video (hot celebrity problem), that's okay. This is because KDA would require\n          to consume from all the shards of the same video. 1 Aggregator can aggregate the view count of 1 or \n          more videos. However, no 2 different Aggregator can aggregate for the same video (that would beat the purpose)\n      i. Since the Event Aggregator has a tumbling window of 1 hour, 1 day and 1 month, we need to three different \n         tables with the same schema where bucketId represents some UUID, bucketWindow is the time range and \n         the third column called TopK is the JSON blob of all videoId->ViewCount. \n      j. KDA Aggregates the view count of the videoId and then sort the VideoID based on view count and then \n         write it to the table with BucketID, Bucket Window and Top K at the end of the window period. \n\n\n2. Display TopK videos\n    a. When a User makes a GET request, it goes to the TopKQuery Service which retrieves the startTimestamp and the window\n        period from the API request and prepares the window range. \n    b. Based on the window, it queries the table with the window range and retrieve the TopK where K = 1000.\n    c. Based on the input provided by the user, it takes the top K from 1000 and return it back to the user.\n\n3. Walk me through how KDA manages these overlapping tumbling windows simultaneously for the same video view event.\n    a. Assuming that there is only 1 KDA running, we can configure the tumbling window of 1 hour, 1 day and 1 month in KDA.\n    b. KDA takes the responsibility of aggregating data from all the Kinesis shards and sort them as per the video count (Max Heap) in every window.\n    c. So, as soon as the hour window is about to collapse, KDA writes to the Database and starts a new tumbling window of 1 hour \n        whereas other tumbling window of 1 Day and 1 Month is still retained.\n    d. KDA has a feature of checkpointing the aggregated data in S3. So, even through KDA crashes, it can resume the aggregation as the data is still present in Kinesis \n         and it can retrieve the last aggregated value from S3 and resume aggregation. So, there is no fear in writing towards the end of the tumbling period.\n    e. Let's evaluate the situation where multiple KDA instances are running. Each KDA instance would be responsible to aggregate view count of 1 or more videos but \n        no 2 KDA instances should aggregate view count of same video.\n    f. If there are N KDA instances and everyone is sorting based on tumbling window of 1 hour, we need a two-layer architecture system where we have 1 more layer of \n       KDA which consumes the aggregated data from multiple KDA shards and then aggregate them and sort them. The last layer of KDA won't have a tumbling window \n       but it will simply consume the data from multiple N KDA shards and write it to the DB (after aggregation and sorting)\n\n4. How do you guarantee tens-of-milliseconds latency for top K queries even at peak demand?\n      a. Since I am already aggregating the TopK data per bucket in the DB, the TopKQuery micro-service won't have to do any computation.\n      b. However, during peak demand, the number of calls to the Database would exponentially increase. In order to get the database bottlenect for READ pattern, \n          we will have a cache in front of the DB which will load the most frequent bucket in its memory such that when GET requests are called, we can directly fetch \n          the data from cache instead of DB. It will solve the database bottleneck problem as well as latency improvement will be seen.\n      c. Additionally, when the new bucket becomes more viral and it leads to cache miss, we can avoid the thundering herd problem by batching the similar request into \n          1 and fetching from the database and then writing it to cache and then returning to the user.\n      d. Every request has a start timestamp and the window period. The main responsibility of the TopK Query microservice is to generate the time range \n           based on start timestamp and the window period. TopK would have timeRange --> Count Map in its in-memory. \n      e. Given that our SLA is around 200ms, we will wait for a max of 30-50ms or 100 requests. Once our batch is complete, we will make a single cache call and \n           if it results in a miss, we will retrieve from the DB, update the cache and then return to the users.\n      f. Cache Call - 10ms, DB call - 50ms Cache update - 10ms. This accumulates to 50 + 70 = 120ms which is still less than 200ms SLA.\n\n\n5. How would you extend the design to support sliding windows (e.g., last hour at arbitrary minutes)?\n     a. KDA has support of sliding windows and every new sliding window can start at an interval of 1 minute. So, I can use this strategy to ask KDA to write the 1 minute sliding window to the DB.\n     b. Post that asynchronously, we can spawn a CRON job to aggregate the minute sliding window data to form Hour Sliding window data and then use \n         Hour Sliding window data to Day and then to Month.\n     c. For example if 5:01 - 5:02 has TopK videos and 5:02-5:03 has TopK videos, 5:01-6:01 hour window will aggregate the TopK videos of all 60 minute buckets and generate the TopK for the \n         hour window bucket (all done asynchronously)\n     d. Now, when TopK Query service receives a query for 5:01 - 6:01, it will find the pre-computed TopK in the database or cache as CRON job helped to construct the day/hour/month buckets.\n     e. Remember that we should not increase the sliding window period as it will put a constraint on the KDA's memory. \n         For example from 1AM - 2AM and the sliding window length is 1 hour,  KDA needs to maintain 60 sliding windows which will use a lot of memory resources as well as \n         frequently writing to S3 checkpoints. On the other hand for the same example, if the window length is 1 minute, we would still create 60 sliding windows but at any given point, \n         there will always be 1 sliding window. \n     f. If the latency SLA does not need to be met for day or month, we can construct them when the request is made based on start and end timestamp which will save us from \n        CRON job creation (as it may create day or month buckets which are never queried) but we will charged for that.\n\n",
