    },
    {
      "id": "FyK6PhfG33jSyWCjqFJGF",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 265.99851800392616,
      "y": -1546.9583621537736,
      "width": 1673.2667236328125,
      "height": 3125,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3G",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 835727449,
      "version": 10431,
      "versionNonce": 1629758359,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771289025247,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Functional Requirements -\n   1.  Users should be able to view a unified list of their VMs across regions with \n         node name, region, and current health status.\n   2. Users should be able to filter, sort, and search VMs by attributes such as region, status, tags, and node name.\n   3. Users should be able to configure alert on VM health changes and receive real-time updates without manual refresh.\n   4. Users should be able to view recent status history for a VM.\n\nAssumptions - \n   1. Every Virtual Node will emits metric in periodicity of 10 seconds.\n\nOut of Scope - \n    1. Sliding window can be a follow-up but we will start with Tumbling window\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n   1. The system should be highly available and eventual consistency is fine with respect to VM health change\n   2. The system should be fault tolerant and there should be no data loss.\n   3. The latency to view/search should be within 100-500ms.\n   4. The latency to receive VM health changes should be within 100ms once alert is configured.\n   5. The latency to view status history for a VM should be within 100-500ms.\n\nAPI Routes\n\n1. GET /view/<clusterId> --> Returns list of <VM> with recent status\n     \n{\n     Id\n     clusterId\n     name\n     region\n     tags: [],\n     lastHealthStatus\n     lastHealthCheckTimestamp\n}\n\n2. GET /search?region=<>&status={}&name={}&count={}&last_node_id={} // offset-based pagination --> \n     Returns list of <VM> with recent status\n\n{\n     Id\n     clusterId\n     name\n     region\n     tags: [],\n     lastHealthStatus\n     lastHealthCheckTimestamp\n}\n\n3. POST alerts/ --> alertId and status code\n\n{\n     userId\n     nodeId\n     windowPeriod: 1minute/1hour\n     timestamp\n}\n\n4. GET /history/<nodeId>\n\n{\n     Id\n     clusterId\n     name\n     region\n     tags: [],\n     healthStatus: [<status1, timestamp1>, <status2, timestamp2>]\n}\n\n\nHigh Level Design -\n\nIngestion of Metrics - \n  1. Every VM Node Health is emitted every 10 seconds. Considering a scale of 100K server metrics emitted every second, we cannot write to database directly.\n  2. Instead, we will persist the data in Kinesis stream which has a throughput of 1GB/sec. Considering every metric to be 1 KB, the total throughput would be \n      1GB/sec, which can be consumed by Kinesis.\n  3. A Lambda (Ingestion Service) would consumer the data from Kinesis at its own speed and write it to Time-Series Database.\n  4. Kinesis can horizontally scale with an intent that metrics of a particular node goes to the same shard. Hence, we need to apply sharding based on nodeId.\n  5. Lambda can horizontally scale with a limitation of 10 consumers per Kinesis Shard. It can consumer/poll in batches and write to the database.\n  6. Time-Series Database has features to schedule materialized views. So, when we dump NodeHealthRawData, auto-schedule of materialized views convert\n       them to NodeHealthHourlyData and NodeHealthMonthlyData and more dimensions.\n  7. Time-Series Database is partitioned by time, so creating materialized views asynchronously does not need to scan the database as they can be scan the recent\n       paritions to create NodeHealthHourlyData and NodeHealthMonthlyData.\n         \n\n1. Users should be able to view a unified list of their VMs across regions\n      a. User makes a GET request to VIEW microservice which fetches the relevant node metadata from the DB based on clusterId\n          and then makes a query to Time-Series Database to collect the recent row of NodeHealthRawData where nodeId == {<collected from NodeMetadata>}\n      b. To optimize it further, popular queries for certain Nodes can be cached in a cache with a TTL. Assuming the recent queries would be recent hourly data, we can \n           persist the pre-computed data \"NodeHealthHourlyData\" in Redis Cache with a TTL of 1 hour for certain Nodes. We can have a LRU eviction policy to get rid\n           of least seen node's data.\n\n2. Users should be able to filter, sort, and search VMs by attributes such as region, status, tags, and node name.\n      a. While the database would be helpful to do a simple scan for searching, it would affect the latency SLA of 100-500ms, making it a bad choice for search.\n      b. When a new Virtual Machine is added to the database and when a new raw data is added to Time-Series Database, we can use a trigger and write it to a database or cache\n          with inverted indexes <words>: [<nodeId>], <status>: [<nodeId>], <region>:[<nodeId>]. We can maintain a sorted set of nodeIds with an intent to insert the new status update\n          of a node and delete the existing record of that node. \n      c. Assuming, search throughput is less as compared to view, we can utilize the Redis cache instance which also has inverted indexes.\n      d. If there is a cache miss, we will query the database to evaluate if its meeting the latency SLA. Highly likely, we can spawn an elastic search if there are too many cache misses.\n\n\n3. Users should be able to configure alert on VM health changes and receive real-time updates without manual refresh.\n     a. Users can make an POST request to the Alert Service which will create a record in ALERT database.\n     b. The Alert service can periodically read the data from Time-Series Database and validate if the status changed within the configured time window. \n     c. f the data changed, it can either return the response to the user, given that the connection is bidirectional (web-socket). However, it will cause 2 pain points - \n             1. Every server will keep an eye on the nodeId for which it receive the request. In such cases, if 2 different users make the same request for nodeId for the same window,\n                 both the servers will periodically read the same data and return to the user.\n             2. Additional hits to Time-Series Database, given that it is going via heavy-write from Ingestion service and heavy-read from view microservice.\n     c. Instead, we can spawn a Event aggregation of 2 windows - prev and new which will check the latest status of that node in prev and new window\n         and if that changes, it will write to the topic of the Pub/Sub architecture for the given nodeID and window period.\n     d. The new flow - \n            1. ALERT micro-service will create the record in the ALERT database.\n            2. It will create a new window for that nodeId. If nodeID already exists but have a different window, we will create another window.\n            3. Event aggregation will have 1 or more windows per nodeId.\n            4. ALERT microservice will register itself as the subscriber to the topic concerned about time-window and nodeId. Multiple users can be connected to similar users with different\n                configurable parameters. In that case, the server will maintain an in-memory map <TopicId>:[<WS1, WS2>].\n            5. Once the aggregator publishes the message to Pub/Sub about prev/new change of status per nodeId and the tumbling window period, iit will route the request to the ALERT\n                servers which will query the in-memory map to fetch the list of websocket connections and return the response to them.\n\n4. Users should be able to view recent status history for a VM\n     a. User will make a call to VIEW microservice and if there's a cache miss for pre-computed data, it will query the Time-series database for the already pre-computed materialized view\n         and it will fetch the history.\n\n\n      \n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Functional Requirements -\n   1.  Users should be able to view a unified list of their VMs across regions with \n         node name, region, and current health status.\n   2. Users should be able to filter, sort, and search VMs by attributes such as region, status, tags, and node name.\n   3. Users should be able to configure alert on VM health changes and receive real-time updates without manual refresh.\n   4. Users should be able to view recent status history for a VM.\n\nAssumptions - \n   1. Every Virtual Node will emits metric in periodicity of 10 seconds.\n\nOut of Scope - \n    1. Sliding window can be a follow-up but we will start with Tumbling window\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n   1. The system should be highly available and eventual consistency is fine with respect to VM health change\n   2. The system should be fault tolerant and there should be no data loss.\n   3. The latency to view/search should be within 100-500ms.\n   4. The latency to receive VM health changes should be within 100ms once alert is configured.\n   5. The latency to view status history for a VM should be within 100-500ms.\n\nAPI Routes\n\n1. GET /view/<clusterId> --> Returns list of <VM> with recent status\n     \n{\n     Id\n     clusterId\n     name\n     region\n     tags: [],\n     lastHealthStatus\n     lastHealthCheckTimestamp\n}\n\n2. GET /search?region=<>&status={}&name={}&count={}&last_node_id={} // offset-based pagination --> \n     Returns list of <VM> with recent status\n\n{\n     Id\n     clusterId\n     name\n     region\n     tags: [],\n     lastHealthStatus\n     lastHealthCheckTimestamp\n}\n\n3. POST alerts/ --> alertId and status code\n\n{\n     userId\n     nodeId\n     windowPeriod: 1minute/1hour\n     timestamp\n}\n\n4. GET /history/<nodeId>\n\n{\n     Id\n     clusterId\n     name\n     region\n     tags: [],\n     healthStatus: [<status1, timestamp1>, <status2, timestamp2>]\n}\n\n\nHigh Level Design -\n\nIngestion of Metrics - \n  1. Every VM Node Health is emitted every 10 seconds. Considering a scale of 100K server metrics emitted every second, we cannot write to database directly.\n  2. Instead, we will persist the data in Kinesis stream which has a throughput of 1GB/sec. Considering every metric to be 1 KB, the total throughput would be \n      1GB/sec, which can be consumed by Kinesis.\n  3. A Lambda (Ingestion Service) would consumer the data from Kinesis at its own speed and write it to Time-Series Database.\n  4. Kinesis can horizontally scale with an intent that metrics of a particular node goes to the same shard. Hence, we need to apply sharding based on nodeId.\n  5. Lambda can horizontally scale with a limitation of 10 consumers per Kinesis Shard. It can consumer/poll in batches and write to the database.\n  6. Time-Series Database has features to schedule materialized views. So, when we dump NodeHealthRawData, auto-schedule of materialized views convert\n       them to NodeHealthHourlyData and NodeHealthMonthlyData and more dimensions.\n  7. Time-Series Database is partitioned by time, so creating materialized views asynchronously does not need to scan the database as they can be scan the recent\n       paritions to create NodeHealthHourlyData and NodeHealthMonthlyData.\n         \n\n1. Users should be able to view a unified list of their VMs across regions\n      a. User makes a GET request to VIEW microservice which fetches the relevant node metadata from the DB based on clusterId\n          and then makes a query to Time-Series Database to collect the recent row of NodeHealthRawData where nodeId == {<collected from NodeMetadata>}\n      b. To optimize it further, popular queries for certain Nodes can be cached in a cache with a TTL. Assuming the recent queries would be recent hourly data, we can \n           persist the pre-computed data \"NodeHealthHourlyData\" in Redis Cache with a TTL of 1 hour for certain Nodes. We can have a LRU eviction policy to get rid\n           of least seen node's data.\n\n2. Users should be able to filter, sort, and search VMs by attributes such as region, status, tags, and node name.\n      a. While the database would be helpful to do a simple scan for searching, it would affect the latency SLA of 100-500ms, making it a bad choice for search.\n      b. When a new Virtual Machine is added to the database and when a new raw data is added to Time-Series Database, we can use a trigger and write it to a database or cache\n          with inverted indexes <words>: [<nodeId>], <status>: [<nodeId>], <region>:[<nodeId>]. We can maintain a sorted set of nodeIds with an intent to insert the new status update\n          of a node and delete the existing record of that node. \n      c. Assuming, search throughput is less as compared to view, we can utilize the Redis cache instance which also has inverted indexes.\n      d. If there is a cache miss, we will query the database to evaluate if its meeting the latency SLA. Highly likely, we can spawn an elastic search if there are too many cache misses.\n\n\n3. Users should be able to configure alert on VM health changes and receive real-time updates without manual refresh.\n     a. Users can make an POST request to the Alert Service which will create a record in ALERT database.\n     b. The Alert service can periodically read the data from Time-Series Database and validate if the status changed within the configured time window. \n     c. f the data changed, it can either return the response to the user, given that the connection is bidirectional (web-socket). However, it will cause 2 pain points - \n             1. Every server will keep an eye on the nodeId for which it receive the request. In such cases, if 2 different users make the same request for nodeId for the same window,\n                 both the servers will periodically read the same data and return to the user.\n             2. Additional hits to Time-Series Database, given that it is going via heavy-write from Ingestion service and heavy-read from view microservice.\n     c. Instead, we can spawn a Event aggregation of 2 windows - prev and new which will check the latest status of that node in prev and new window\n         and if that changes, it will write to the topic of the Pub/Sub architecture for the given nodeID and window period.\n     d. The new flow - \n            1. ALERT micro-service will create the record in the ALERT database.\n            2. It will create a new window for that nodeId. If nodeID already exists but have a different window, we will create another window.\n            3. Event aggregation will have 1 or more windows per nodeId.\n            4. ALERT microservice will register itself as the subscriber to the topic concerned about time-window and nodeId. Multiple users can be connected to similar users with different\n                configurable parameters. In that case, the server will maintain an in-memory map <TopicId>:[<WS1, WS2>].\n            5. Once the aggregator publishes the message to Pub/Sub about prev/new change of status per nodeId and the tumbling window period, iit will route the request to the ALERT\n                servers which will query the in-memory map to fetch the list of websocket connections and return the response to them.\n\n4. Users should be able to view recent status history for a VM\n     a. User will make a call to VIEW microservice and if there's a cache miss for pre-computed data, it will query the Time-series database for the already pre-computed materialized view\n         and it will fetch the history.\n\n\n      \n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
